item.title:
Last week in Ethrex L1 development we focused on getting Pectra through the finish line, to be able to support the upcoming forks in the testnets. We're finishing the last bits but should be ready for the Holesky update next week. We also fixed several issues across the board.
- Implemented EIP-2935 (Serve historical block hashes from state) - Implemented EIP-7685 (General purpose execution layer requests) - Implemented EIP-6110 (Supply validator deposits on chain) - Changed sync default to full sync in post merge testnets - Added `--dev` mode to simulate a simple consensus engine - Add a fix that to avoid discarding peers that were already connected - Refactored and removed some feature flags - Improved negotiation of capabilities between peers - Fix issues regarding peers abruptly disconnecting due to getting an EOF - Refactored snap sync algorithm to start early storage healing and paralellize downloading of accunts - Modularized sync code - Added missing serialization for an EIP-7702 transaction - Fixed returned capabilities when calling `engine_exchangeCapabilities`
LEVM We made significant progress on EF Tests compatibility, particularly for pre-Istanbul forks. We're now down to approximately 600 remaining state transition tests to pass. Additionally, we've begun implementing the necessary hooks for L1->L2 deposit transactions, which will enable us to transition the L2 to using LEVM.
Changelog: - Improved test coverage across multiple test suites including `eip3651_warm_coinbase`, `stArgsZeroOneBalance`, `stBugs`, `stSStoreTest`, and `stCreate2` - Fixed various test cases related to Byzantium, Constantinople, and Spurious Dragon forks
Performance We've identified and started working on several key performance improvements for Ethrex (both L1 and L2). Our main focus areas include:
- Optimizing database flush operations by implementing batch processing for state updates post-block execution - Implementing state snapshots to reduce trie traversal overhead during state queries - Improving transaction filtering and ordering efficiency during block building - Reducing mempool lock contention when handling high volumes of `sendRawTransaction` RPC calls
To better track these improvements, we're adding gas/s metrics to the node for monitoring execution performance. We're also developing a new I/O-intensive test contract to complement our existing CPU-focused fibonacci contract for more comprehensive load testing.

item.description:
Last week in Ethrex L1 development we focused on getting Pectra through the finish line, to be able to support the upcoming forks in the testnets. We're finishing the last bits but should be ready for the Holesky update next week. We also fixed several issues across the board.

- Implemented EIP-2935 (Serve historical block hashes from state)
- Implemented EIP-7685 (General purpose execution layer requests)
- Implemented EIP-6110 (Supply validator deposits on chain)
- Changed sync default to full sync in post merge testnets
- Added `--dev` mode to simulate a simple consensus engine
- Add a fix that to avoid discarding peers that were already connected
- Refactored and removed some feature flags
- Improved negotiation of capabilities between peers
- Fix issues regarding peers abruptly disconnecting due to getting an EOF
- Refactored snap sync algorithm to start early storage healing and paralellize downloading of accunts
- Modularized sync code
- Added missing serialization for an EIP-7702 transaction
- Fixed returned capabilities when calling `engine_exchangeCapabilities`

LEVM
We made significant progress on EF Tests compatibility, particularly for pre-Istanbul forks. We're now down to approximately 600 remaining state transition tests to pass. Additionally, we've begun implementing the necessary hooks for L1->L2 deposit transactions, which will enable us to transition the L2 to using LEVM.

Changelog:
- Improved test coverage across multiple test suites including `eip3651_warm_coinbase`, `stArgsZeroOneBalance`, `stBugs`, `stSStoreTest`, and `stCreate2`
- Fixed various test cases related to Byzantium, Constantinople, and Spurious Dragon forks

Performance
We've identified and started working on several key performance improvements for Ethrex (both L1 and L2). Our main focus areas include:

- Optimizing database flush operations by implementing batch processing for state updates post-block execution
- Implementing state snapshots to reduce trie traversal overhead during state queries
- Improving transaction filtering and ordering efficiency during block building
- Reducing mempool lock contention when handling high volumes of `sendRawTransaction` RPC calls

To better track these improvements, we're adding gas/s metrics to the node for monitoring execution performance. We're also developing a new I/O-intensive test contract to complement our existing CPU-focused fibonacci contract for more comprehensive load testing.
